SIMPLE: specious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Specious
<hw>Spe"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>speciosus</ets>good-looking, beautiful, specious, fr.
<ets>species</ets> look, show, appearance; cf. F.
<ets>sp⟦eacute⟧coeux</ets>. See <er>Species</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Presenting a pleasing appearance; pleasing in form or look;
showy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some [serpents] <qex>specious</qex> and beautiful to the eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Richardson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rest, far greater part,⟦br⟧
Will deem in outward rites and <qex>specious</qex> forms⟦br⟧
Religion satisfied.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Apparently right; superficially fair, just, or
correct, but not so in reality; appearing well at first view; plausible;
<as>as, <ex>specious</ex> reasoning; a <ex>specious</ex>
argument.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Misled for a moment by the <qex>specious</qex> names of religion,
liberty, and property.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In consequence of their greater command of <qex>specious</qex>
expression.</q> <rj><qau>J. Morley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Plausible; showy; ostensible; colorable;
feasible. See <er>Plausible</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Spe"xious*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Spe"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speck</ent>⟦br⟧
